                    <div class="section" id="objectives">
                        <div class="section-header"><h3>OBJECTIVES</h3></div>
                        <div class="section-content"><div class="section-content-wrapper"><div style="position: relative; margin: 20px 0; padding: 0;"><div class="key-definition-box"><h4>LEARNING OBJECTIVES</h4><div><p>By the end of this module, you will be able to:</p></div></div></div></div><div class="section-content-wrapper"><div class="interactive-activity-wrapper"><div class="accordion-container"><div class="accordion-item"><div class="accordion-header">1. Explain the core principles of diversity, equity, and inclusion (DEI) and why they matter in the workplace</div><div class="accordion-content"><p><b>What this means:</b> You will develop a clear understanding of what diversity, equity, and inclusion mean in practice, not just as concepts but as principles that directly influence team performance, employee wellbeing, and organisational success. You will be able to articulate why DEI is a business priority and a leadership responsibility.</p><p><b>Aligned to:</b> Understanding DEI principles</p><p><b>KSB Link:</b> K9 – Understands how to build and maintain a diverse and inclusive team</p></div></div><div class="accordion-item"><div class="accordion-header">2. Recognise different types of unconscious bias and explain how they can influence leadership decisions</div><div class="accordion-content"><p><b>What this means:</b> You will learn to identify common forms of unconscious bias, such as affinity bias, confirmation bias, and the halo effect. More importantly, you will understand how these biases can subtly affect your judgement when recruiting, delegating, giving feedback, or making everyday decisions as a leader.</p><p><b>Aligned to:</b> Recognising unconscious bias</p><p><b>KSB Link:</b> K10 – Understands approaches to equality and diversity</p></div></div><div class="accordion-item"><div class="accordion-header">3. Demonstrate inclusive leadership behaviours that create a sense of belonging for all team members</div><div class="accordion-content"><p><b>What this means:</b> You will explore the specific actions and behaviours that inclusive leaders display, such as active listening, seeking diverse perspectives, challenging exclusionary behaviour, and ensuring equitable access to opportunities. You will reflect on your own leadership style and identify areas for development.</p><p><b>Aligned to:</b> Inclusive leadership behaviours</p><p><b>KSB Link:</b> B3 – Acts with integrity, being fair and consistent in approach</p></div></div><div class="accordion-item"><div class="accordion-header">4. Apply practical strategies to build and sustain a positive, inclusive team culture</div><div class="accordion-content"><p><b>What this means:</b> You will gain practical tools and techniques for shaping team culture, including how to establish inclusive team norms, facilitate open dialogue, address microaggressions, and create psychologically safe environments where everyone feels valued and able to contribute their best work.</p><p><b>Aligned to:</b> Building and sustaining positive team culture</p><p><b>KSB Link:</b> S12 – Builds trust with the team through consistent behaviour and clear communication</p></div></div></div></div></div><div class="section-content-wrapper"><div class="text-content-render"><p><b>How these objectives support your apprenticeship:</b></p><p>Each learning objective has been designed to align with the knowledge, skills, and behaviours (KSBs) required for the Team Leader Level 3 standard. Completing this module and the associated activities will provide you with:</p><ul><li><b>Off-the-job (OTJ) learning evidence</b> – demonstrable learning that counts towards your 20% off-the-job training requirement</li><li><b>Portfolio evidence</b> – reflections and activities that can be included in your apprenticeship portfolio</li><li><b>Gateway preparation</b> – knowledge and skills that will support your End-Point Assessment (EPA)</li></ul></div></div></div>
